    body: "Living alone in retirement can be peaceful, independent, and deeply satisfying. It also means there is no one in the next room to call for help if you fall, have a stroke, or take a bad reaction to a new medication. The Centers for Disease Control reports that one in four adults over 65 falls each year, and a senior who lies on the floor for more than an hour faces higher risks of pneumonia, kidney injury, and hospitalization, even when the original fall was minor. The fix is not to give up living alone. The fix is to set up a clear, written emergency plan so that help reaches you fast on the worst day.\n\nA good emergency plan has three layers. The first layer is the people who would notice if you went quiet, sometimes called check-in buddies. These are friends, neighbors, or relatives who hear from you on a predictable schedule and know to act if they do not. The second layer is the technology that can summon help when you cannot reach a phone, such as a medical alert button, a fall-detection smartwatch, or a smart speaker with emergency calling. The third layer is the paperwork that tells first responders who you are, what medications you take, and who to call when they arrive. All three layers work best together. A medical alert button is useless if nobody is named on the account. A check-in buddy cannot help if they do not have a key. Paperwork is wasted if first responders cannot find it.\n\nThis guide walks through how to choose two or three check-in people, the daily and weekly habits that keep them in the loop, the medical alert and smart-home tools that work well in 2026, the information first responders need at the front door, and the small house tweaks that turn a home into a safer place to live alone. None of this is hard or expensive. Most single seniors can set up a complete emergency plan in one weekend for under 200 dollars.",
