    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "A solo aging support group is a small circle of older adults who meet on a regular schedule to talk through the practical and emotional questions of aging without a spouse or close family. Topics often include where to live, how to plan for medical care, how to handle the holidays alone, how to build a network of trusted friends, and how to face the harder questions about mortality and final wishes. The conversations are often warm, sometimes funny, and almost always more honest than the small talk at a typical senior center. Members say the groups give them a place to think out loud with peers who truly understand the daily reality of being on your own in later life.\n\nThe demand for these groups has grown sharply. AARP estimates that more than a third of Americans age 65 and older now live alone, and the share of seniors who never married is rising every year. National organizations such as the AARP Solo Agers Project, the Solo Aging Hub, and the National Association of Social Workers have responded with toolkits, webinars, and local chapter listings. Community organizations such as senior centers, libraries, churches, synagogues, and Area Agencies on Aging now host solo aging discussion groups in most U.S. metro areas, and many smaller towns have joined the trend. If you cannot find one nearby, online groups on Zoom, Facebook, and Meetup are active every day of the week.\n\nThe quality of a solo aging group depends on three things. First, the facilitator should keep the conversation balanced and confidential. Second, the group should be small enough, usually 6 to 12 members, for everyone to speak. Third, the meetings should follow a predictable schedule so trust can build over time. Drop-in groups have their place, but the strongest bonds form in groups that meet weekly or twice a month with mostly the same faces. Many participants attend the same group for years.\n\nThis guide walks through where to look for a group in your area, how to evaluate a group in the first one or two visits, what to do if you cannot find a group nearby, and how to start one yourself with a small amount of help. Plan to try two or three groups before settling on a home base. The right group can become a powerful piece of your chosen family and a major contributor to your health and happiness in later life.",
